  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The mortality of acute renal failure (ARF) remains to be high (around 60-70%) despite
      manifold improvements in ICU care. At present, it is not clear if the method chosen for renal
      replacement therapy, i.e. intermittent haemodialysis (IHD) or continuous haemofiltration
      (CVVH), might impact on the outcome of these patients. For this purpose, a prospective
      randomised clinical study of the effect of continuous versus intermittent renal replacement
      therapy on the mortality and outcome of acute renal failure will be performed.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
